Area: Cherokee, AL
Description:
['* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall is expected.', '* WHERE...A portion of central Alabama, including the following
county, Cherokee.', '* WHEN...Until 915 AM CST Saturday.', '* IMPACTS...Flooding of rivers, creeks, streams, and other low-lying
and flood-prone locations is imminent or occurring.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 908 AM CST, Reporting gauges indicate elevated levels
along the Chattooga River Above Weiss Lake. This will cause
lowland flooding along the Chattooga River Above Weiss Lake.
- River levels are expected to crest today and fall below minor
flood stage tonight.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Cedar Bluff, Gaylesville, Cornwall Furnace Park, Eastern
Weiss Lake and Western Weiss Lake.']

Area: Monroe, AL
Description:
['* WHAT...Flooding caused by excessive rainfall is expected.', '* WHERE...A portion of south central Alabama, including the
following county, Monroe.', '* WHEN...Until 1000 AM CST Friday.', '* IMPACTS...Numerous roads remain closed due to flooding. Streams
continue to rise due to excess runoff from earlier rainfall.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...
- At 1251 AM CST, Monroe County Emergency Management reported
numerous roads in central and southern Monroe County remain
closed due to 5 to 10 inches of rain that occurred Thursday
evening. While the heavy rain has ended, small creeks and
streams are still either cresting or continuing to rise. This
is resulting in the continued flooding of some roads. In
addition, some roads may have experienced washouts,
particularly on county dirt roads.
- Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Monroeville, Frisco City, Peterman, Uriah, Excel, Megargel,
Manistee, Goodway, Mexia Crossing, Mexboro, Mexia, Jeddo,
Halls Crossroads, Ollie, West Monroeville, Palmers
Crossroads, Homewood, Drewry, Monroeton and Renson.']

Area: Anchorage
Description:
['Another round of snow has developed across Anchorage and along
the Glenn Highway early this morning. Due to the dry nature of
this snow, it can be easily blown around and reduce visibilities,
especially in the wake of other vehicles. The snow from yesterday
evening plus the new snow this morning could make for slippery
surfaces across town. The snow is expected to taper off by late
morning to mid- day.', 'Motorists are urged to use caution and slow down when traveling.
For the latest road conditions call 5 1 1 or visit 511.alaska.gov.']

Area: Misty Fjords
Description:
['* WHAT...Heavy snow. Additional snow accumulations of 10 to 15
inches.', '* WHERE...Misty Fjords including Hyder.', '* WHEN...Until 9 AM AKST Friday.', '* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snowfall rates will continue to be high
through Friday morning. Around 15.8 inches has already fallen at
Hyder as of 3 am. A transition to rain is possible sometime
Friday morning. However confidence remains low on the timing of
the change over. An earlier or later transition time may greatly
effect snowfall amounts.']

Area: Northeast Prince William Sound
Description:
['* WHAT...Blizzard conditions occurring. Additional snow
accumulations of 1 to 2 inches. Winds gusting as high as 40
mph.', '* WHERE...Thompson Pass.', '* WHEN...Until 9 AM AKST this morning.', '* IMPACTS...Plan on slippery road conditions. Widespread blowing
snow could significantly reduce visibility to one quarter mile.
Wind chills around 25 below zero during this time could cause
frostbite on exposed skin in as little as 30 minutes.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Winds will shift and decrease sharply later
this morning, bringing an end to blizzard conditions. However,
snow will linger through the day and could reduce visibility at
times.']

Area: Glacier Bay; Eastern Chichagof Island
Description:
['* WHAT...Snow and periods of freezing rain. Additional snow
accumulations of 1 to 4 inches. Ice accumulations less than a
tenth of an inch.', '* WHERE...Gustavus, and Hoonah.', '* WHEN...Until noon AKST today.', '* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Wet snow may be
difficult to manage.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Another round of snow and mixed
precipitation is ongoing across the Icy Strait Corridor through
Friday. Expect areas near sea level to transition to rain
through Friday morning. Confidence is low regarding the exact
timing of the change over to rain. An earlier or later
transition time may effect total snowfall amounts at sea level.']

Area: Juneau Borough and Northern Admiralty Island
Description:
['* WHAT...Snow and periods of light freezing rain expected.
Additional snow accumulations of 1 to 4 inches. Ice
accumulations less than one tenth of an inch.', '* WHERE...Juneau.', '* WHEN...Until noon AKST today.', '* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Wet snow may be
difficult to manage. Freezing rain will cover exposed surfaces
with a coating of ice.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Snow and freezing rain are expected to
continue through Friday morning north of Lemon Creek. Downtown
and Douglas have warmed above freezing and are seeing a mix of
rain and snow. The airport will likely transition to rain before
the Mendenhall Valley and further out the road. Confidence is
low regarding the exact timing of the transition to rain and the
freezing rain potential, which could greatly affect total
snowfall amounts. Areas that receive more mixed precipitation
and change to rain sooner will likely have lower snowfall
amounts.']

Area: Taiya Inlet and Klondike Highway; Haines Borough and Lynn Canal
Description:
['* WHAT...Heavy snow expected. Total snow accumulations of 8 to
15 inches. Winds gusting as high as 35 mph.', '* WHERE...Haines, Haines Highway, Skagway, Dyea, and the
Klondike Highway to White Pass.', '* WHEN...From 6 AM Thursday to 6 PM AKST Friday.', '* IMPACTS...Travel could be very difficult. Wet snow may be
difficult to manage.', '* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Another round of heavy snow is ongoing
across Upper Lynn Canal through Friday evening. Expect areas
near sea level to mix with rain Friday evening before precip
diminishes Friday evening. Confidence is lower regarding the
exact timing of the change over to rain. An earlier or later
transition time may effect total snowfall amounts at sea level.']

Area: Upper Koyukuk Valley
Description:
['* WHAT...Blowing and drifting snow with low visibility and wind

Description:
['Precipitation has ended for our region but very cold temperatures
will continue through Saturday morning. There is a concern for
black ice this morning as any wet spots will have refrozen overnight,
potentially impacting the morning commute. Many places will get
above freezing today but any lingering snow or ice will be able to
refreeze on the roadways again tonight. Black ice will once again
be possible Saturday morning, especially in low-lying areas and
bridges and overpasses. Untreated roadways and sidewalks that have
not completely dried out will also be at risk for ice. Motorists
should exercise caution by slowing down and increasing following
distance.', 'Very cold temperatures are expected this morning with temperatures
in the single digits and sub zero wind chills in many locations.
These very cold temperatures will continue through Saturday
morning as well. Prepare for the cold weather by protecting pipes,
plants, pets, and checking on the vulnerable.']

Description:
['With plenty of residual moisture in place and temperatures at or
below freezing, many roadways across Middle Tennessee are slippery
and icy. Temperatures early this morning range from the mid 20s
in the northwest to near 30 degrees along the Cumberland Plateau.
We still expect some additional light mixed precipitation to move
across the mid state early this morning. This additional
precipitation will only act to further impact the hazardous
driving conditions across the area.', 'Bridges and overpasses will likely be the most problematic with
ice formation likely. Be especially cautious and aware that black
ice, or ice you cannot see, is likely and very dangerous even
though it is not visible.', 'Temperatures today are not expected to warm above freezing.
Therefore, improving conditions due to some drying may not occur
until afternoon at the earliest. If you must travel across the mid
state area this morning, slow down, and allow extra time to reach
your destination.']

Description:
['Precipitation has ended for our region but very cold temperatures
will continue through Saturday morning. There is a concern for
black ice this morning as any wet spots will have refrozen overnight,
potentially impacting the morning commute. Many places will get
above freezing today but any lingering snow or ice will be able to
refreeze on the roadways again tonight. Black ice will once again
be possible Saturday morning, especially in low-lying areas and
bridges and overpasses. Untreated roadways and sidewalks that have
